{{Infobox scientist | name = Corina Brussaard | image = Corina Brussaard.jpg | birth_name = | nationality = [[Netherlands]] | fields = Antarctic [[ecovirology|viral ecology]] | workplaces = [[Institute for Biodiversity and Ecosystem Dynamics]] | alma_mater = [[University of Amsterdam]] | website = https://www.nioz.nl/staff-detail?id=140024 }}
'''Corina Brussaard''' is a leading scientist for Antarctic viral ecology<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.nioz.nl/news-detail/corinabrussaard-professor_en|title=Corina Brussaard appointed professor - NIOZ|website=www.nioz.nl|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.dw.com/en/women-climate-scientists-conquer-antarctica/a-16650017|title=Women climate scientists conquer Antarctica {{!}} Environment {{!}} DW.COM {{!}} 06.03.2013|last=(www.dw.com)|first=Deutsche Welle|website=DW.COM|access-date=2016-07-26}}</ref> working for the Royal Institute of Sea Research (NIOZ) and is a Special Professor of Viral Ecology at the [[Institute for Biodiversity and Ecosystem Dynamics]] of the [[University of Amsterdam]] (UvA).<ref name="Amsterdam">{{Cite web|url=http://ibed.uva.nl/news-events/events/content/events/2015/09/phd-defence-ceremony-of-kristina-mojica/phd-defence-ceremony-of-kristina-mojica/cpitem/link/c.p.d.e.brussaard|title=prof. dr. C.P.D. (Corina) Brussaard - IBED - University of Amsterdam|last=Amsterdam|first=Universiteit van|website=ibed.uva.nl|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nioz.nl/news-detail/corinabrussaard-professor_en|title=Corina Brussaard appointed professor - NIOZ|website=www.nioz.nl|access-date=2016-08-02}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Brussaard was educated at [[University of Groningen]] (RUG), The Netherlands, studying marine biology, and microbial ecology.<ref name=":2">{{Cite web|url=http://ibed.uva.nl/news-events/news/content/2013/02/prof.-dr.-c.p.d.-brussaard-special-chair-viral-ecology.html|title=Prof. dr. C.P.D. Brussaard Special Chair Viral Ecology - IBED - University of Amsterdam|last=Amsterdam|first=Universiteit van|access-date=2016-07-27}}</ref> She defended her PhD thesis on ‘Phytoplankton cell lysis and ecological implications’ in 1997. She was awarded a Marie Curie TMR-grant supplied by the EC for 2 year Post Doctoral research at the University of Bergen, Norway.<ref name=":2" /> In 2000 she started as Independent Research Fellow at the NIOZ [[Royal Netherlands Institute of Sea Research]] where she was involved in the EC-FP5 project BIOHAB (Biological Control of Harmful [[Algal bloom|Algal Blooms]] - role of [[eutrophication]]) studying the growth and mortality of HAB-species, while at the same time setting up a virus ecology research program. She became a Senior Research Scientist at the NIOZ in 2003,<ref name=":2" /> and obtained a special chair in Viral Ecology in the [[Institute for Biodiversity and Ecosystem Dynamics]] (IBED) at the [[University of Amsterdam]] (UvA) in 2013.
==Career and impact== Brussaard is a leading scientist for Antarctic viral ecology,<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> the quantitative and qualitative significance of viral mediated mortality of microbes for population dynamics, community composition, and the production and efficiency of the [[Pelagic zone|pelagic]] food web. Brussaard's research focuses on studying the interaction between viruses and their host algae in relation to [[climate change]], and more specifically on how this interaction is affected by environmental factors, such as CO<sub>2</sub> concentration and temperature, the availability of light and nutrients.<ref name=":2"/><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Maat|first=Douwe S.|last2=Crawfurd|first2=Katherine J.|last3=Timmermans|first3=Klaas R.|last4=Brussaard|first4=Corina P. D.|date=2014-05-15|title=Elevated CO2 and Phosphate Limitation Favor Micromonas pusilla through Stimulated Growth and Reduced Viral Impact|url=http://aem.asm.org/content/80/10/3119|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=80|issue=10|pages=3119–3127|doi=10.1128/AEM.03639-13|issn=0099-2240|pmc=4018922|pmid=24610859}}</ref>
Brussaard studies the ecological role viruses play in the sea, combining field work and detailed laboratory studies.<ref name="Amsterdam"/> She investigates the importance of microbial (phytoplankton and bacteria) cell death rates<ref>{{Cite journal|last=CPD|first=Brussaard|last2=GJ|first2=Gast|last3=FC|first3=van Duyl|last4=R|first4=Riegman|date=1996-12-05|title=Impact of phytoplankton bloom magnitude on a pelagic microbial food web|url=http://www.int-res.com/abstracts/meps/v144/p211-221/|journal=Marine Ecology Progress Series|volume=144|pages=211–221|doi=10.3354/meps144211|bibcode=1996MEPS..144..211B}}</ref> and its consequences for the pelagic [[Biogeochemical cycle|biogeochemical cycling]] (carbon, nutrients including iron), as well as isolation of novel [[algae]]-infecting [[viruses]] (e.g. viruses infecting ''[[Phaeocystis]]'' belonging to the recently named large-genome [[Mimiviridae]] family).<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brussaard|first=C. P. D.|last2=Short|first2=S. M.|last3=Frederickson|first3=C. M.|last4=Suttle|first4=C. A.|date=2004-06-01|title=Isolation and Phylogenetic Analysis of Novel Viruses Infecting the Phytoplankton Phaeocystis globosa (Prymnesiophyceae)|url=http://aem.asm.org/content/70/6/3700|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=70|issue=6|pages=3700–3705|doi=10.1128/AEM.70.6.3700-3705.2004|issn=0099-2240|pmc=427783|pmid=15184176}}</ref> She also discovered the first [[Double-stranded RNA viruses|dsRNA virus]] that infects [[protist]]s<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brussaard|first=C. P. D|last2=Noordeloos|first2=A. A. M|last3=Sandaa|first3=R. -A|last4=Heldal|first4=M|last5=Bratbak|first5=G|date=2004-02-20|title=Discovery of a dsRNA virus infecting the marine photosynthetic protist Micromonas pusilla|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S0042682203008286|journal=Virology|volume=319|issue=2|pages=280–291|doi=10.1016/j.virol.2003.10.033|pmid=14980488}}</ref> and lipid membrane-containing ''[[Micromonas]]'' viruses.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Martnez|first=Joaqun Martnez|last2=Boere|first2=Arjan|last3=Gilg|first3=Ilana|last4=Lent|first4=Jan W. M. van|last5=Witte|first5=Harry J.|last6=Bleijswijk|first6=Judith D. L. van|last7=Brussaard|first7=Corina P. D.|date=2015-01-12|title=New lipid envelope-containing dsDNA virus isolates infecting Micromonas pusilla reveal a separate phylogenetic group|url=http://www.int-res.com/abstracts/ame/v74/n1/p17-28/|journal=Aquatic Microbial Ecology|volume=74|issue=1|pages=17–28|doi=10.3354/ame01723}}</ref> Additionally she has developed methods for the rapid detection<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brussaard|first=Corina P. D.|date=2004-03-01|title=Optimization of Procedures for Counting Viruses by Flow Cytometry|url=http://aem.asm.org/content/70/3/1506|journal=Applied and Environmental Microbiology|language=en|volume=70|issue=3|pages=1506–1513|doi=10.1128/AEM.70.3.1506-1513.2004|issn=0099-2240|pmc=368280|pmid=15006772}}</ref> and enumeration of viruses, and for measuring cell lysis<ref name="Baudoux 207–217">{{Cite journal|last=Baudoux|first=AnneClaire|last2=Noordeloos|first2=Anna A. M.|last3=Veldhuis|first3=Marcel J. W.|last4=Brussaard|first4=Corina P. D.|date=2006-10-10|title=Virally induced mortality of Phaeocystis globosa during two spring blooms in temperate coastal waters|url=http://www.int-res.com/abstracts/ame/v44/n3/p207-217/|journal=Aquatic Microbial Ecology|volume=44|issue=3|pages=207–217|doi=10.3354/ame044207}}</ref><ref name="Baudoux 207–217"/> rates as a consequence of viral infections.
Brussaard is the President of the International Society of Microbes (ISVM)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://isvm.org/officers.html|title=Officers - ISVM.org|website=isvm.org|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> and is also the Chair of the Netherlands Scientific Committee on Oceanic Research (SCOR) Committee from 2006 until 2016 and its secretart from 2014-2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.knaw.nl/en/advisory-work/advisory-councils-and-committees/organisaties/164/akademiaorganisation_membersview|title=SCOR - Nederlandse SCOR Commissie — KNAW|website=www.knaw.nl|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.scor-int.org/Executive_Committee/Brussaard.htm|title=Scientific Committee on Oceanic Research (SCOR), Corina Brussaard|website=www.scor-int.org|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> She was also a member of the Netherlands Polar Committee from 2010–2014<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nwo.nl/en/research-and-results/programmes/Netherlands+Polar+Programme/organisation|title=Organisation|last=Marianne|website=www.nwo.nl|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> and is a Fellow of the [[American Society for Microbiology|American Academy Microbiology]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://academy.asm.org/index.php/fellows-info/fellows-elected-in-2016|title=Fellows Elected in 2016|last=Seglem|first=Erin|website=academy.asm.org|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> and of the Council for Earth and Life Sciences<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.knaw.nl/en/members/experts/7271|title=Brussaard, Prof. dr. C.D.P. (Corina) — KNAW|website=www.knaw.nl|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> of the [[Royal Netherlands Academy of Arts and Sciences]].
Brussaard’s research has received interest from radio, newspapers and magazines.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rd.nl/vandaag/buitenland/klimaat-antarctica-verrast-onderzoekers-1.447592|title=Klimaat Antarctica verrast onderzoekers|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nd.nl/cookies-op-nd-nl.1449892.lynkx|title=Cookies op ND.nl|website=Nederlands Dagblad|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.nrc.nl/nieuws/2013/01/28/nederlands-lab-op-antarctica-open-1201734-a934111|title=Nederlands lab op Antarctica open|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.trouw.nl/tr/nl/4332/Groen/article/detail/3425986/2013/04/15/Nederlandse-onderzoekers-terug-van-Antartica.dhtml|title=Cookies op Trouw.nl|website=www.trouw.nl|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref> Moreover, Brussaard was a guest on the Dutch television show [[Pauw & Witteman]] on 23 January 2013 to discuss the then new Dutch [[Dirck Gerritsz Pomp|Dirck Gerritsz]] Laboratory.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://programma.vara.nl/pauwenwitteman/media/206811|title=Pauw en Witteman|website=Pauw en Witteman|language=nl-NL|access-date=2016-07-25}}</ref>
In March 2016, Brussaard was selected as a Fellow of the American Academy of Microbiology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.asm.org/index.php/asm-newsroom2/press-releases/94046-78-fellows-elected-to-the-american-academy-of-microbiology|title=78 Fellows Elected to the American Academy of Microbiology|access-date=2017-01-09}}</ref>
