[[File:Djibtelcom2.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Djibouti Telecom]] (Djibouti Télécommunication Co.) headquarters in [[Djibouti (city)|Djibouti City]].]]
'''Media in [[Djibouti]]''' is controlled by the government.

==Telecommunications==
{{main|Telecommunications in Djibouti}}
From [[Djibouti (city)|Djibouti City]], telephone connections are available by satellite to [[Europe]] and the West and by land line to the main cities and towns of the interior. There were 9,500 mainline telephones and 23,000 cellular phones in use throughout the country in 2003.

==Television, radio and Internet==
[[File:Radtdjhd4.png|thumb|right|A news show on [[Radio Television of Djibouti]].]]
All media are government controlled. [[Radio Television of Djibouti|Radio Djibouti]] began broadcasting in the 1940s, during the colonial period in [[French Somaliland]].<ref name="d10">{{cite book|last=Dubnov|first=Helena|title=A Grammatical Sketch of Somali|page=10|year=2003|publisher=Rudiger Koppe Verlag|location=Koln}}</ref> In 1983, Djibouti inaugurated a powerful state-owned AM radio transmitting station, built with [[France|French]] and FRG funds. A television service was first introduced in 1967. Both are state run and broadcast in [[Arabic language|Arabic]], [[French language|French]], [[Somali language|Somali]] and [[Afar language|Afar]]. As of 2001, there were 1 AM and 2 FM radio stations and 1 television station. In 1997, there were 77 radios and 37 television sets per 1,000 population. [[Internet]] access was available to about 6,500 subscribers in 2003.

==Print==
Djibouti has one primary weekly newspaper, the government owned [[La Nation de Djibouti]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.lanationdj.com/| title=La Nation de Djibouti }}</ref> which had a circulation of 4,300 in 2000. Each political party is allowed to publish a public journal. There are several opposition-run weeklies and monthlies that operate freely.

==Freedom of speech==
{{main|Freedom of the press in Djibouti}}
The constitution provides for freedom of speech and the press, but the government severely restricts journalism, and international observers say that Djibouti lacks freedom of the press.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://rsf.org/en/djibouti |title=Djibouti |publisher=RSF |date= |accessdate=2017-04-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author= |url=https://freedomhouse.org/report/freedom-press/2015/djibouti |title=Djibouti &#124; Country report &#124; Freedom of the Press &#124; 2015 |website=Freedomhouse.org |date= |accessdate=2017-04-29}}</ref>

